      <h2>Budget Tool Box Buying Tips</h2>
      <p>Getting the most value from a budget tool box comes down to a few simple strategies:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Buy for today's tools, not tomorrow's:</strong> A common mistake is buying a box way larger than you need, then filling it with empty space. Buy the size that fits your current inventory, and add storage as your collection grows.</li>
        <li><strong>Modular is more economical long-term:</strong> A modular system lets you add boxes one at a time. You're not forced to replace everything when your needs change.</li>
        <li><strong>Prioritise the latch and handle:</strong> These are the failure points on any budget box. Read reviews specifically about latch durability before buying.</li>
        <li><strong>Consider rolling:</strong> A budget box with good wheels is more practical than a premium box without them. The BLACK+DECKER set's rolling base dramatically reduces daily wear and tear on your body.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Should You Ever Buy a Cheap Tool Box?</h2>
      <p>There's a difference between "budget-friendly" and "cheap." A $15 plastic tool box from a big-box store will likely crack, warp, or lose its latch within a year of professional use. That's not a bargain — it's a recurring expense.</p>
      <p>The products in this guide are budget-friendly, not cheap. They deliver professional-grade performance at prices that respect your bottom line. A box that lasts five years instead of one is always the cheaper option in the long run. Invest in quality, even on a budget.</p>

